  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How can I connect a non-smart TV with my smartphone?",
  "response": "Connecting a non-smart TV with your smartphone can be accomplished in several ways. Here are some common methods:\n\n### 1. HDMI Cable and Adapter\nUsing an HDMI cable is one of the most straightforward methods:\n- **Check your smartphone**: Many modern smartphones have HDMI output capabilities, but they might need adapters. If your phone has a USB-C port, you'll need a USB-C to HDMI adapter. If it has a Micro-USB port, you might need a specific kind of adapter.\n- **Connect the adapter to your phone**: Plug one end of the adapter into your phone.\n- **Connect the HDMI cable to the adapter and TV**: Plug the HDMI cable into the adapter and the other end into the HDMI port on your TV.\n- **Switch your TV to the HDMI input**: Use your TV remote to change to the proper HDMI input.\n\n### 2. Using Wireless HDMI Dongles\nThere are various wireless HDMI solutions that can connect your smartphone to your TV:\n- **Chromecast**: This device plugs into your TV\u2019s HDMI port and lets you cast content from your phone via Wi-Fi. Follow the setup instructions that come with Chromecast.\n- **Miracast**: Many Android phones support Miracast, which mirrors your phone\u2019s screen wirelessly. Your TV needs to have a Miracast receiver, or you can use a Miracast dongle.\n\n### 3. MHL (Mobile High-Definition Link)\nSome phones support MHL, which requires an MHL to HDMI adapter and an HDMI cable.\n- **Get an MHL adapter**: Ensure your phone is MHL compatible.\n- **Connect the adapter to your phone**: Plug the MHL adapter into your phone\u2019s charging port.\n- **Connect HDMI cable**: Connect one end of the HDMI cable to the adapter and the other end to the TV.\n- **Power the adapter if needed**: Some MHL adapters might require external power. Plug them into a USB power source.\n- **Switch to the HDMI input**: Use your TV remote to switch to the appropriate HDMI input.\n\n### 4. RCA Cables and Adapter\nIf your TV lacks HDMI ports, you can connect using RCA cables and a suitable adapter, though the resolution will be lower.\n- **Get a suitable adapter**: Generally, you\u2019ll need an HDMI to RCA converter or similar.\n- **Connect the converter**: Plug the adapter/converter into your phone's HDMI adapter or output port.\n- **Connect RCA cables to your TV**: Plug the RCA cables into the converter and your TV\u2019s RCA input ports (typically yellow, red, and white).\n- **Change the TV input**: Use your TV remote to switch to the RCA input.\n\n### 5. USB to TV\nSome TVs allow you to play content directly from a USB drive, which means you could transfer files from your smartphone to a USB drive and then plug the USB drive into your TV.\n- **Transfer files**: Move your media files to a USB drive using an OTG (On-The-Go) adapter if needed.\n- **Plug USB drive into TV**: Insert the USB drive into the USB port of your TV.\n- **Navigate to USB input**: Use your TV remote to navigate through your TV input selections to find the USB drive content.\n\n### 6. DLNA (Digital Living Network Alliance)\nIf both devices support DLNA, you can stream content over a local network.\n- **Download a DLNA app**: Find and install a DLNA app on your smartphone.\n- **Connect both devices to the network**: Ensure that both your TV and smartphone are connected to the same Wi-Fi network.\n- **Stream content**: Use the DLNA app to stream media from your smartphone to your TV.\n\nThese methods should enable you to connect your non-smart TV to your smartphone efficiently. Be aware that the exact steps might vary slightly depending on your specific devices and their compatibility.",
